\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 What about relatives living nearby?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 In London you mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Yes.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid1928298 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 We had practically none living in London. Her parents had a very beautiful house for some of the time in Queen Anne's Gate.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Friends, did they come around to see you a lot?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Yes. Mostly by arrangement, you know, to dinner or whatever, drinks.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 And what about neighbours, did they call casually? Presumably they didn't.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Well, neighbours.... Somebod
y happening to live next door didn't necessarily mean you knew them at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Your home wasn't rented in London, was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
No, I bought it. And then bought Rumney's house.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Would you say that there was a difference in people's attitude towards clas
s in London than here? I mean a different one from here?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Oh, I should think so. Well, either ... I mean, here you know a lot of people slightly, and roughly who and what they are and, of course, in London everybody; except your own and definite friend
s who are of your own sort, are complete strangers. You don't know anything about them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
There's just a couple of extra questions about people who went to boarding school. Was there anything particular about boarding school that you remember?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 I'm a
fraid I'm not clear as to what that question is.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Was there anything particular that you think is worth mentioning about life at boarding school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
I was very lucky, I think, in my particular school because Sanderson as - you'll find there he was ver
y advanced in his views and regarded citizenship really as more important than scholarship, really. And really rather deprecated athleticism and competition. What he wanted was co-operation and so on and he was very ... well, what we would call very 'left
' in his views, and that came off on me to some extent.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid917675 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 
\par I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Were you ever homesick, or did you feel resentful about being sent away to school?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid1928298 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Not resentful. I expected it to be pretty beastly and so it was, to begin with, and I expected it to be beast
ly. It wasn't quite as beastly as I'd expected.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 A typical day at school, was it very different from a typical day at home?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Oh, yes, entirely. I mean, everything was regimented, you worked to a bell.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 And meals were good, or bad?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Very bewil
dering when you've never been to any sort of school before, not even a day school. And to be the only new boy, one felt very strange, indeed. It was in many ways a very good school indeed, and what I resented was these compulsory games. I was reasonably g
ood at them but they didn't interest me. I resented time wasted on games when I might have been exploring that lovely countryside around Northamptonshire.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 There's just one more thing, and that's about the jobs that your children did when they were adult.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Well, my eldest daughter, she was a natural artist and when she'd left Dartington, went back there as an art teacher. And then she was a painter, decorating things, did a certain amount of book illustration, and then got to decorating pottery. And t
hen with her husband Ewan Cooper-Willis started up and now runs the Portmeirion Pottery in Stoke-on-Trent. And the other daughter, she got a double first in biology at Oxford and then went on to Cambridge on an advanced course thing, where she met her hus
band who is also a biologist, a New Zealander, and she lives out in New Zealand and has five children of her own there. And she's carrying on now with ... she's a lecturer at the University there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 What about your brothers' jobs what are they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Well,
 my elder brother, he succeeded my father as Glasfryn. And then the second one was killed in South Africa, Boer War. And the third one, Martin, he ultimately ran the family slate quarries, Blaenau Ffestiniog, with the \{missing\}
 Quarries. He died about two 
years ago, and now his son runs them and he lives in Ireland, but Wern belongs to him now and he comes over. And then the youngest one, he was agricultural. He died about 15, 20 years ago I should think and now I'm the only survivor of the original six.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 What about your daughter's husbands? You mentioned the one in New Zealand.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid1928298 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
You know, he's the top biologist. Well, he's really the head of the Government Institute of Agriculture in New Zealand. That's their main industry, you see, and he's very muc
h tops in biology and agriculture and animal husbandry, and all that. And they've got, as I say, five children. One of them's just been staying with us. They've all been to stay here at one time or another.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 And then there's your other daughter's husband.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
There are only the two; Susan, who's pottery and Charlotte who's New Zealand.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 I was just wondering about Susan's husband.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Ewan Cooper-Willis?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid917675 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Yes.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid2062548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Well, he's an economist. He and our son, Christopher, who was killed, shared rooms 
at King's College Cambridge. And he's an economist, stockbroker, financier, that sort of thing. And, you know, Eton and King's College. Scholar, I think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 One of the things we left out was what magazines did your parents read, if any?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 The Paper, th
e daily paper they took was The Standard, which is long dead, and The Daily Graphic.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 They didn't take any magazines, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
I suppose so, but probably over my head, you see, I didn't realise what they had. Probably most of those are dead now, Blackwoods, or whatever they were. I. can't recall any.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 When you were at home as a child do you remember being read to aloud by your mother or father?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Oh, yes. Scott, mostly. Scott and Dickens, the sort of standard nourishment of the young in those days. And Water Babies, Kingley's, and Black Beauty which my mother illustrated. She was a very good artist and especially good at horses.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Did your parents ever read to each other?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
No. My father read tremendously the classics, I mean, you know, in Latin and Greek, and did Chess problems and astronomical mathematics, corresponded with various old dons on these subjects.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 The other question was: do you have any idea why your mother was Conservative?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2062548 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
I wouldn't have said she was... She was awfully non-political, really, like all her family. You see, there was a large ... she was one of 8, or 7, I think. Four girls and 3 boys. My uncle, John Graves of \{missing\}
 Dick Graves of Wern and Uncle Ned who had a Scottish property was left him by an uncle o
f his. And then Mrs. Hansard, Aunt Edie, who married one of the Parliamentary Report, Hansard's, who was rector of Bethnal Green. She didn't like that very much. And then Lady Smyth and Lady Williams, and my maiden Aunt Hilda who was delightful, lived at 
\{missing\}
, you know, Tremadoc, and did it up beautifully. Everything was sort of Recency. If you walked into a room there you might have been one of Jane Austen's characters and found it exactly as she would have expected it. You know, exactly the right fur
niture and pictures, and collected books about the period and so on and so forth. And none of them were political. Well, insofar as they were at\bullet 
all they were Conservative, because they were rather shocked as my uncle, Sir Osmond Williams who was ... his father had been the first ever Liberal Member for Merioneth and then he became the same and they rather looked down their noses at him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
The other thing was you suggested, when you answered the questions before that neither you or your family ever brought pressure to bear on people as to which way they should vote.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid917675 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Certainly not.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid2379911 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 But apparently you seemed to suggest that you knew of people who did this, other families, maybe, in the area. Or do you know of any examples of this sort of thing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Oh, well, yes, notoriously. Old Sir Hugh Ellis Nanny of \{missing\}
 who stood in opposition to Lloyd George and L.G. only got in by about 20 votes. And how truly I don't know, it was said that he evicted or threatened to evict tenants who didn't vote for him, which was common form.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
This is why the people at Essex were interested in this, because they knew it was common form and wondered about this area.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
And was just becoming a scandal. I mean, had been accepted as normal practice heretofore. I mean, the tenant bloody well voted with his landlord, or out he went. And the same, probably with the household insofar as they had votes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Yes, because it was before the secret ballot and everything?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Do you ever remember anyone being described as a 'real lady' or 'a real gentleman'?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Oh, yes. As a compliment, certainly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Was it used towards your family ever, did you hear it being ...?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2379911 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Of course, one didn't hear so much of one's own family being discussed as other people. Of course, 
I think what they envisaged as a gentleman was rather different to what one would now. I mean it would be more his outward show and outward behaviour rather than his real nature.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 There was a practice that was fairly common in England in a community, if
 people wanted to show disapproval for the acts of certain individuals in that community they used to stand outside the door and play what was called 'rough music', which was sort of banging on tin cans and making a lot of noise and generally sort of maki
ng public the scandal that was supposed to be going on inside the house.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Ah, yes, well I never encountered that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 I haven't heard about it being done in this area at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 No. It's a nice idea, but \{
laughter\}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Yes, 'cos they used to do it ..
. very respectable people, apparently, who ... I don't know, wife-beating or something was going on and they would go and make a lot of noise outside. The other thing that was forgotten I think was you said you had 5 brothers.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid917675 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Yes.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid15746018 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 And when we came to talk about what they all did, you know, all their occupations, we only discussed four of them. Could we run over what their occupations were?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Well, my elder brother, he did ... at Cambridge, engineering and that was the beginning of electrificati
on and various things and he, in partnership with a Cambridge friend set up engineering works, electrical switch gear, chiefly, that sort of thing. And it seemed alright and then the electrification boom rather died down a bit, and they were a young firm 
a
nd ... I don't know how well managed or not, I mean they were very enthusiastic and enterprising, but I don't think they knew much about the business, and after a few years the thing had shut up. So that was the end of that as far as he was concerned. And
 
then he did a bit more on that line as manager for a cousin, Trevor Williams, who was chairman of the gramophone company which became an immense and flourishing affair and he had, other interests ... other engineering interests. My brother was manager of 
o
ne of these for a bit and he got, I think, rather fed up with London, and he then took to agriculture and very much for agricultural co-operation. He was a great friend of Sir Horace Plunkett, you know, the Irish Co-Operative man, and of ... oh what's his
 name, of Aberystwyth? The great brass man. I'll remember in a minute probably. Oh, there were a whole group of them. He was very much in with that and ran ... started the \{missing\}
 Agricultural Co-Operative and that sort of thing, and was quite enterprising in his own farm. He grew tobacco which was not a great success \{laughter\}
 and he tried all sorts of things like that. He never made any money, in fact he lost and gave away quite a lot, you know, supporting these things. And my youngest brother, too. In 
fact, at one time they farmed together, they bought in a lot of farms at Glasfryn under one management, you see, this co-operative thing, and lost heavily on that. And then my eldest brother took up forestry and he was more successful at that and which hi
s
 son, Roger, at Glasfryn now, he turned into a very big thing. Until he recently got ill he was very successful. He won all the gold medals this last year for forestry, and so forth. And then Martin, who was next to me, he was engineering, too. And with t
h
e Thorneycroft Company in Cheshire, who made mining machinery and he was quite a good geologist too. And he was sent out by Thorneycroft to erect and supervise their machinery in South Africa, Johannesburg and he was out there for ... oh, I think about 8 
o
r 10 years as their South African representative. And indeed, until the First War when he joined up as a gunner, he ... in fact he'd been a volunteer gunner, territorial gunner. Stayed out there until after the War when my uncles, who were getting old, co
axed him back as manager to the \{missing\}
 Quarries, Blaenau Ffestiniog, where he continued and became ultimately chairman of the ... managing director, I think, and then chairman and so on, until he died. And then his son, John, is now the chairman and of c
ourse, the whole thing has dwindled tremendously. I think at one time they had about 500 employees there, or more, and was the biggest underground working in the world, and it's gradually gone down. You see the Welsh slate trade never really recovered fro
m the great Penrhyn strike which lasted for 3 years. It cast a very long shadow, and foreign slates came in and so on. And then Oakley, which was even bigger than the Quarry, it was shut up altogether.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 So we've had three of them. You've talked about three of your brothers, Martin, the eldest one ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Oh yes. Well, there was Richard, who died as a child. You see, my grandfather, who came from England, was an amateur geologist, keen mountaineer walker, that sort of thing and on one of his expeditions, 
pottering about with rock, thought he'd found a good spot up at Blaenau, good slate-making rock and ... The things I have left out of my autobiography, that I thought were interesting to put in. I was talking about my grandmother, my maternal grandmother.
 
"According to my mother, and his portraits, a fine large handsome man, very kind and popular with a prominent nose. He was a keen amateur geologist and on a prospecting ramble through North Wales, thought a spot he lighted on at Blaenau Ffestiniog looked 
p
romising for slate, arrange to lease the site, with a small gang of miners and set about his digging. For months they dug in vain and were on the point of giving up in despair, my grandfather's capital and credit having been almost entirely exhausted, whe
n
 they suddenly struck it rich and uncovered a vein of the very best slate-making rock. My grandfather's faithful and pious old foreman was so moved and impressed by this merciful tarn in their fortunes that he insisted that his master should, immediately 
k
neel down with him and thank God for their deliverance from disaster. Under my grandfather's expert and genial management the quarry flourished and ultimately became really big business, allowing him to indulge in his other non-geological interests, build
ing and hunting. At first he mostly hunted in Cheshire where he was much taken by the half timbered black and while old buildings in the area and unfortunately adopted that style for the two houses he built himself and his large family at \{missing\}
 close to
 his quarry and then, more romantically, at the entry to Aberglaslyn Gorge - what they call Aberglaslyn Hall, now. His lust for both hunting and building still upon him, he moved to Warwickshire there to install himself and his family and horses at Berryc
o
te on the edge of Leamington. No happier, architecturally, than his previous two Welsh houses, but with plenty of mis-applied fine craftsmanship lavished on elaborately carved armourial furniture that ultimately came to Glasfryn, until later dispersed els
e
where, but that there always seemed a little uncomfortable in its polished nouveau richness. Dying at Brighton at 75, he had kept up his hunting almost to the last, despite my grandmother's pleas that he should give it up. To show his continued fitness an
d
 absence of fatigue after a hard day he would sometimes place a couple of her drawing room chairs back to back and clear them in a running jump, still in his top boots. All his seven children had been born at Tanyran, William Maddocks," and so on, I go on
 
about William Maddocks, which I left out of the other thing.".... each. Christened in the church, every other such occasion being marked by the presentation of a new Welsh steeple hat to the nurse." Just why only every other, I don't know, except that he 
h
ad no idea how many children he might end up with and no doubt the development of the quarry still needed all the capital that he could find for it. He was always generous as well as careful and his steadily increasing wealth in no way changed him as a ma
n
, though it did enable him to leave all his children handsomely provided for, especially, of course, his sons who further developed the family quarries became rather grand three rich uncles, each large and handsome and remarkable in his own individual way
, and to me memorable. As to the daughters ... and so on. He rather liked the present Sir Osmond Williams, you know, whom we call Michael Baldwyn.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Could you say briefly about how much you think your governess influenced you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Not much. The first one
, Miss Barker, who was a gentle, rather nice creature, we rather bullied. She suffered from what we now call migraine, sick headaches, and we always amongst ourselves called her The Carcase \{laughter\}
 and I think we were rather unkind to her because she wa
s very nice. And then she was succeeded by a very robust, bustling little person, Miss Skinner, who was a Newham graduate, a sort of female tutor, really, whose forte was mathematics which interested my father, really, more than it did us, and, I think, b
o
tany, but we didn't have any of that. And she was terribly jolly and rather like a sort of female boy scout, you know, and rather trying to join in our activities and show us the way. And I didn't much like her, really. She was too bustling and jolly and 
a
ll that, rather like a scout master. But well educated and ... I remember vowing at one time, she'd outraged me and I would never, never be friends with her, and it's about the only vow I ever made and kept. Though my mother liked her, and my father liked
 her because of her mathematics. Oh, she was a very ... perfectly good little person.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid917675 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 I want to go on now and talk about the school, the boarding school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 About Oundle?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Didn't I talk about Oundle last time?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid15746018 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Yes. The only thing that they were very interested in, because it seemed to be a sort of atypical school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Oh, it was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Progressive?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Very progressive.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Well, they were interested in the comparison between that and what was a sort of typical school of the day. What was different about Oundle?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Well, I gave that, I think fairly clearly in that book. I mean, Sanderson ... In the end he admitted to being a near-communist and all along he was very ... sort of anti-privilege and very much set on what he called produci
ng a good general level rather than an intellectual aristocracy and a ruck of also-rans and he wanted to get a bulk output of good citizens, really, and very much for co-operation as against competition, and all that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 What about the day to day discipline within the school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Well, as I said there. Outwardly he was a very sort of comfortably habited, quiet person but could either simulate or produce tremendous rages when he thought it politic. I think it was pumped up for a purpose and was ... quite f
requently administered beatings, of which I had my share.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Did you have to wear uniforms at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Uniform? No. Well, one wore what might be called sort of infant version of City gents' outfit, you know, black coat and striped trousers and black t
ie and school cap. The school cap was compulsory in order that first of all you could be recognised in the town and elsewhere, but also to take it off to masters. A sign of submission.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid917675 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 I think we could go on to talk about Cambridge now.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid15746018 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Well Cambridge, I avoided part I of the Little Go \{missing\}
 which was then a compulsory examination and by, I suppose, School Certificate, that sort of thing, but that didn't take in classics for the complete Little Go \{missing\} either had to pass in Paley's Evidenc
es of Christianity, which you've probably never heard of but anyhow was a great thing, or in Latin and Greek which, on the modern side in Oundle I had not done, and so my last school holiday was clouded by the necessity of mugging up Latin and Greek for t
h
is one silly examination. And my father was only too willing to tutor and so I spent a large part of my holiday working away at Latin and Greek and heartily disliking it, as I'd no interest apart from this examination, as it were, and didn't know how I'd 
d
one until I got a telegram from my tailor who lived opposite Senate House where the results were posted up on the door there, you see a telegram saying 'passed Little Go fourth class. Congratulations'. And my father I remember saying it was really rather 
h
umiliating because he'd won every possible prize and scholarship, both at school and Cambridge, tutor of his college, that I should be congratulated on a fourth class in the most elementary examination there was. But anyhow, then I was supposed to be read
i
ng Natural Science and under the best auspices, J. J. Thompson, a famous lecturer, and I forget who the others were - I was at Trinity - and ... But gradually my interest in science was more or less submerged by my growing interest, it had .always been th
e
re, in architecture and I would find my otherwise blank pages - I had notebooks at these lectures - being covered with architectural sketches, colonnades and triumphal arches, and whatnot, instead of with the appropriate notes of the particular lecture. A
n
d so I came to the conclusion after a year, after 3 terms, that I was really wasting my time and my father's money, and that I'd like to drop it all with a view somehow of reaching architecture. And it was then that I ... they said 'well, architecture is 
n
ot really a profession, it's a sort of poor job somewhere between the local art teacher and local auctioneer and surveyor. You make a living somehow and having done that then you can take up architecture as a hobby'. And the nearest route to any sort of a
ffluence seemed to me to go into engineering and join my brother's factory as a laboratory experimentalist, testing things, and so on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
And then, as I said, when that showed signs of folding up owing to a slump, I removed myself as experimentalist to an
 electrical inventor, who was very able old boy, in Westminster, and was there for the best part of a year. And then I couldn't bear that any longer, it was a very fiddling sort of job, you know, testing new inventions. And I was shut up in a dark attic w
h
ere, you know, you had a reflector and the readings of your instruments were shown on a screen. And anyhow, I was longing for more exciting architecture than Victoria Street offered and I went down with 'flu quite badly and whilst I was away I plucked up 
s
ufficient courage ... when I was recovering, to write to him to say that I wasn't coming back. And I got a rather clinging letter back from him saying 'you mustn't desert me like that' and I knew that if I did go back he was a very nice old boy, very pers
u
asive - that I would probably be argued into staying against my instinct. And so I never went back, even to recover my Aquascutum and notebooks and all the rest of my stuff, for fear of being caught. And this was before I had any ... I didn't know anythin
g
 about architecture, really, I was no architect. I was only by looking up Architecture in the London Telephone book that I found a place called the Architectural Association School, that I made contact and went there a term. But then, by good luck and fam
i
ly jobbery I got one or two small jobs and started on them, which involved contractors and clients and suppliers, of this and that coming to see me at the school and I didn't do a ... Certain lectures I didn't want to miss and so I used to take in whoever
 
have come to see me into the, lecture and talk to them and take notes at the same time, which I thought the height of efficiency, to absorb and emit wisdom at the same time. But it was considered very subversive, and upsetting for the other students, whic
h
 was quite right, and so I was sent for by the principal and said, 'look here, you've, either got to give up using the school as your private office, or go'. I said, 'I quite agree with you, it must be very disturbing'. But I'd always understood it was a 
great hurdle to get your first job and as I seem to be launched I think I'd better stick to it. He said 'I think you're probably quite right.' I went off with his blessing, with just a few small jobs and I was so launched .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 So you were only at Cambridge for a year, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Only a year, under Dr. Montague Butler, where his great nephew is now, Lord Butler.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 How were you taught at Cambridge? Did you have tutors as well as lecturers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Oh, yes, you have your college tutor. He didn't do much. He was a classicist, mine was, Mr. Duff.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 How did people in general get on with the tutors? What sort of relationship was there between ... ?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Well, it was fairly slight. They didn't take much ... Of course, he was a classicist, anyhow, and he probably didn't really understand what I was doing, or much approve of it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Did You have any friends there who influenced you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Oh, yes, quite a number. I think they're all dead long since. One character I saw a good deal of then, and in London afterwards, was
 the rather notorious Horace De Vere Cole, you know, who organised the Dreadnought Hoax and, you know, dug up part of Piccadilly, you know, fenced off, pretending to be council workers, and then left the police to sort out the traffic jam and remove these
 obstructions. He was doing all sorts of things like that. An amusing but rather embarrassing friend to have.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 What was the discipline like at Cambridge?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Well, it never impinged on me. I mean, it was all very reasonable, it seemed to me. You weren't
 allowed to be drunk and disorderly in the streets. You had to be in by a certain time, or else contrived to climb in, and I was a perfectly law-abiding undergraduate and I don't remember any scandals while I was up there, or important rows.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 How would you describe the other students there, what sort of people were they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Well, they were, I suppose, almost exclusively from public schools. Trinity was largely furnished by Eton. I think I was the only Oundle boy there. It was then quite a minor public 
school, you see, it hadn't made its name. And certain colleges had their specialities, like Cains College was partly ... largely medical, Trinity Hall was law; Magdalen, which was a very small college, a very nice old college, you know, where ... it's got
 
the Pepys library and all that, and earlier that had been a sort of waste paper basket for rowdy young noblemen and such who were turned out of Trinity, and they went to and had a very jolly time at this little college down on the river. But now Benson, I
 
think, rather brought it up. That had its ... had been founded by the Braybrooks of Audley End, the great house, you know, near Saffron Walden, who were hereditary masters as part of their patrimony, but that was then reduced to the fact that they could n
o
minate the master, rather like the old thing of advowsons in the church, you know, you were patron of a living and you could choose the parson. And then they could choose the, master. And that still goes on to the extent that the present Lord Braybrook ha
s
 to ... or anyhow, is courteously asked to approve the appointment of a new master. But it is quite a serious intellectual place. Now, Lord Blackett was there and ... when he came out of the Navy. My father had been there at Cambridge, and my grandfather 
a
nd my great-grandfather. And my grandfather and great-grandfather used to ride up to Cambridge on Welsh ponies from here and return by coach and then go up the next day on another Welsh pony, which they'd sell in Cambridge, you see. Whether it was their o
wn particular bright and economical idea, I don't know, or whether it may have been fairly general, but that's what they did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 Were there any women there when you were there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
Oh, yes. In fact, my Godmother, Annie Clough, sister of the poet, was the 
first principal of Newnham, and then her niece was principal, Theena Clough, when I was up there, and so I used to go to Newnham a certain amount. And when she retired I thought 'well, that's the end of Newnham'. Not a bit of it, because Annabel's cousin,
 
Colonel Strachey, succeeded her as principal and so we were still persona grata at Newnham. There were relatively few, they were rather rare and ... I mean, there were far more of them, I think, who were purely academic, they weren't such a jolly lot of g
irls as they apparently are now. And you couldn't have them in your rooms, and that sort of thing. There was none of that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid15746018 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
I was just wondering how people, other students, male students, viewed educated women, because it wasn't really the thing for women to have too much education in those days, was it? How did you feel about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid423966\charrsid8738534 CW:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid423966 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
I think at the time I felt it was rather unnecessary, and, you know, the view was - what was it? "Habishad the Ishmaelite, Shabby Hag the Newnhamite" \{laughter\}. They ten
ded to be rather swots, as they were called at school, and they weren't very alluring. Whether they had a special uniform or not I can't remember, I don't think so.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid917675 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid423966 I:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid8738534\charrsid8738534 I think that's probably enough, thank you very much.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f0\fs24\insrsid917675\charrsid8738534 
\par }}